inference:
Using the identity $\binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}$, we have $\binom{13}{9} = \binom{13}{13-9} = \binom{13}{4}$.
Therefore, $\binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{9} = \binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{4} = 2\binom{13}{4}$.
$\binom{13}{4} = \frac{13!}{4!9!} = \frac{13 \times 12 \times 11 \times 10}{4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = \frac{13 \times 12 \times 11 \times 10}{24} = 13 \times 11 \times 5 = 143 \times 5 = 715$.
So, $\binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{9} = 2 \times 715 = 1430$.

Final Answer: $\boxed{1430}$
